  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash occurs in
preparePlanForEpilogueVectorLoop() due to the assertion that EPResumeVal must
exist. EPResumeVal is found by scanning the scalar preheader's PHI nodes for a
canonical IV resume value. The matcher used is too permissive, causing multiple
PHIs to match, making find_singleton return nullptr and triggering the
assertion.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nSCEV indicates a canonical IV with trip
count 1051 and a separate induction. The pass turns on epilogue vectorization.
The repro shows two PHIs in the preheader:\n  - %vec.epilog.resume.val = phi i32
[ 1024, %middle.block ], [ 0, %iter.check ], [ 0, %vector.main.loop.iter.check
]\n  - %bc.resume.val = phi i32 [ 0, %middle.block ], [ 0, %iter.check ], [ 0,
%vector.main.loop.iter.check ]\nEPI.VectorTripCount is the constant i32 1024. The
current predicate matches both PHIs because it requires (a) incoming value from
MainLoopIterationCountCheck is 0, and (b) all incoming values are either
VectorTripCount or 0. Since bc.resume.val has all incoming values 0, it
erroneously matches too. With two matches, find_singleton returns nullptr, hence
the assert fires.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\n- The predicate in
preparePlanForEpilogueVectorLoop() at lines 9784\u20139796 does not require that
there is an actual incoming equal to EPI.VectorTripCount; it only allows that
incoming values are either VectorTripCount or 0. This admits PHIs that are all
zeros, like bc.resume.val, leading to ambiguity. The earlier VPlan-level check
that decides whether to create the canonical resume PHI is stricter (it checks
for a PHI with operands [VectorTC, 0]). The IR-level check needs similar
strictness.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\n- File:
llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp, lines 9784\u20139796 (inside
preparePlanForEpilogueVectorLoop)\n  Change the find_singleton predicate to
additionally require that the PHI has at least one incoming equal to
EPI.VectorTripCount, not just that all are in the set {VectorTripCount, 0}.
Concretely, compute a HasVectorTC flag via any_of(P.incoming_values(), Inc ==
EPI.VectorTripCount) and require HasVectorTC to be true, along with the existing
checks. This disambiguates and ensures only %vec.epilog.resume.val matches and
%bc.resume.val is rejected.\n\n  Rationale: This aligns the IR-level matching
with the stricter VPlan-level pattern (created in preparePlanForMainVectorLoop)
and fixes the ambiguity introduced by other resume PHIs that may be all
zeros.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy strengthening the pattern to require the presence of
EPI.VectorTripCount among incoming values, preparePlanForEpilogueVectorLoop()
will reliably find the canonical IV resume PHI, avoiding multiple matches and the
resulting assertion. This resolves the crash for the provided reproducer and
improves robustness for similar cases with multiple preheader PHIs.",
